{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the success of captive breeding and reintroduction programs based on the primates' rearing environment?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the rearing environment of primates, the success of captive breeding and reintroduction programs varies. For primates born and reared in cages, one study in Brazil found that most reintroduced golden lion tamarins did not survive over seven years or had higher mortality than wild-born tamarins (1594). In French Guiana, a controlled study showed that more squirrel monkeys born and reared in cages died or were returned to captivity compared to wild-born monkeys (1594). Additionally, a study in Madagascar indicated that the diet of reintroduced black-and-white ruffed lemurs from cages did not overlap with that of wild lemurs (1594). In contrast, for primates with limited free-ranging experience, one study in Madagascar found their diet did overlap with wild lemurs (1595). However, another study in Madagascar showed that most reintroduced black-and-white ruffed lemurs with limited free-ranging experience died over five years (1595). Conversely, studies in the Republic of Congo and Gabon found that most reintroduced western lowland gorillas with limited free-ranging experience survived for periods ranging from nine months to four years (1595). For primates born and raised in a free-ranging environment, a study in Brazil reported that only two out of three reintroduced black lion tamarins survived over four months (1596). A controlled study in Madagascar found that the diet of reintroduced black-and-white ruffed lemurs from a free-ranging environment overlapped with that of wild lemurs (1596).",
