{
  "query": "To manage human-wildlife conflict in residential areas, what are the benefits and potential drawbacks of relocating primates?",
  "relevant_summary": "There is no evidence to suggest the effects of relocating primates to non-residential areas [1423] or the effects of translocation to prevent gene contamination [1536]. However, when reintroducing primates in groups, two studies in Brazil and Thailand found that primate populations declined, and seven studies in Brazil, French Guiana, Madagascar, and South Africa found that a minority of primates survived for at least 15 weeks to seven years [1567]. In contrast, one study in Belize found that primate populations increased, and another in The Gambia found that a population of introduced chimpanzees increased 25 years after reintroduction [1567]. Additionally, two studies in Madagascar and India found that primate populations persisted for 4-55 years after reintroduction [1567]. Several studies have documented the survival of a majority of primates after reintroduction, with survival periods ranging from two months to five years [1567]. One controlled study in Indonesia reported that all Sumatran orangutans survived for at least three months after reintroduction [1567]. Furthermore, one study in Madagascar found that introduced black-and-white ruffed lemurs had similar diets to wild populations after reintroduction [1567].",
